In the spring of 1945, Allied troops entered German concentration camps and made a systematic film record of the atrocities they saw. The documentary, which contains startling footage from Dachau, Buchenwald and Bergen-Belsen, was left unfinished and stored in a vault of London's Imperial War Museum. In 1985, this somber record of man's capacity for inhumanity was broadcast for the first time by &quot;Frontline&quot; with narration by actor Trevor Howard.

LOADER'S NOTE - This documentary consists almost entirely of raw footage taken by soldiers. It is extremely stark and open, and may be difficult for some people to sit through.
